In article <199407071833.NAA11644@indial1.io.com>, ritter@io.com (Terry
Ritter) writes:

> Actually, the "value" which influences attack is not its actual
> value, but rather the value as perceived by the attacker.  (If you
> have a broken VCR, a burglar may steal it anyway, if s/he does not
> know that it is broken.)

True.  However, the consequences to the user can never exceed the value of
the data to him.  You are welcome to my broken VCR.  Security analysis
deals with both frequency of occurence and with consequences; any analysis
that focuses on one at the expense of the other is flawed.

